The heights of the members of a large sports club are normally distributed. A random sample of 11 members of the club is chosen and their heights, \(x \text{cm}\), are measured. The results are summarised as follows, where \(\overline{x}\) denotes the sample mean of \(x\).

<|ref|>equation<|/ref|><|det|>[[341, 125, 609, 144]]<|/det|>
\[\overline{x} = 176.2\qquad \Sigma (x - \overline{x})^2 = 313.1\]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[111, 155, 876, 189]]<|/det|>
Test, at the \(5\%\) significance level, the null hypothesis that the population mean height for members of this club is equal to \(172.5 \text{cm}\) against the alternative hypothesis that the mean differs from \(172.5 \text{cm}\).
